Get the equation of a circle through the points (1,1),(2,4),(5,3)(1,1),(2,4),(5,3).

I can solve this by simply drawing it, but is there a way of solving it (easily) without having to draw?

Follow these steps:

  1. Consider the general equation for a circle as (x−xc)2+(y−yc)2−r2=0(x−xc)2+(y−yc)2−r2=0
  2. Plug in the three points to create three quadratic equations
    (1−xc)2+(1−yc)2−r2=0(1−xc)2+(1−yc)2−r2=0
    (2−xc)2+(4−yc)2−r2=0(2−xc)2+(4−yc)2−r2=0
    (5−xc)2+(3−yc)2−r2=0(5−xc)2+(3−yc)2−r2=0
  3. Subtract the first from the second, and the first from the third to create two linear equations
    −2xc−6(yc−3)=0−2xc−6(yc−3)=0
    (yc+7)−6xc=0(yc+7)−6xc=0
  4. Solve for the center as
    (xc,yc)=(3,2)(xc,yc)=(3,2)
  5. Plug the values for the center in any of the three quadratic equations above (I choose the first) and solve for rr
    (1−3)2+(1−2)2−r2=0(1−3)2+(1−2)2−r2=0
    5−r2=05−r2=0
    r=5–√r=5
  6. Verify result with GeoGebra (optional)

Based on what I've learnt from this page by Stephen R. Schmitt (thanks to @Dan_Uznanski for pointing the concept out), there's a faster way to do it using matrices:

let ⟨x1,y1⟩,⟨x2,y2⟩,⟨x3,y3⟩ be your 3 points, and let ⟨x0,y0⟩ represent the center of the circle. let A=⎡⎣⎢⎢⎢⎢x2+y2x21+y21x22+y22x23+y23xx1x2x3yy1y2y31111⎤⎦⎥⎥⎥⎥=⎡⎣⎢⎢⎢⎢x2+y212+1222+4252+32x125y1431111⎤⎦⎥⎥⎥⎥=⎡⎣⎢⎢⎢x2+y222034x125y1431111⎤⎦⎥⎥⎥   Note: M11=0⟹⟨x0,y0⟩ is undefined∧the points lie on a line rather than a circle.  x0=12⋅M12M11=12⋅∣∣∣∣22034143111∣∣∣∣/∣∣∣∣125143111∣∣∣∣=12⋅−60−10=3let 〈x1,y1〉,〈x2,y2〉,〈x3,y3〉 be your 3 points, and let 〈x0,y0〉 represent the center of the circle. let A=[x2+y2xy1x12+y12x1y11x22+y22x2y21x32+y32x3y31]=[x2+y2xy112+1211122+4224152+32531]=[x2+y2xy121112024134531]   Note: M11=0⟹〈x0,y0〉 is undefined∧the points lie on a line rather than a circle.  x0=12⋅M12M11=12⋅|21120413431|/|111241531|=12⋅−60−10=3

y0=−12⋅M13M11=−12⋅∣∣∣∣22034125111∣∣∣∣/∣∣∣∣125143111∣∣∣∣=−12⋅40−10=2y0=−12⋅M13M11=−12⋅|21120213451|/|111241531|=−12⋅40−10=2

The radius, rr, can then be calculated with Pythogoras' theorem, or using matrices again:

r2=x20+y20+M14M11r2=x02+y02+M14M11

  • M12(A)M12(A) is a minor of A — the determinant of AA without row 11 or column 22.
  • Lines on either side of a matrix indicate the determinant (e.g. |A||A|) (sometimes written det(A)det(A))

If you have the time, it's really worth learning about matrices — they make a lot of things much faster, and are just generally awesome! KhanAcademy has a pretty easy introduction to matrices and linear algebra.

I'm surprised this one hasn't been mentioned; you can find the equation by using the determinant of a matrix:

∣∣∣∣∣∣x2+y212+1222+4252+32x125y1431111∣∣∣∣∣∣=0|x2+y2xy112+1211122+4224152+32531|=0
This gives the equation of the circle through those three points. This sort of thing can be used in a lot of situations: matrix-determinant solutions are available for any shape I can think of where you're given points that land on the shape.

Implementing this on a computer involves having a thing that calculates determinants; to do it numerically you'll need to apply the cofactors method to avoid multiplying the variables in.

  • I just tried it and don't like it. I'd suggest using 3d plane operations: you can find the center by intersecting the perpendicular bisector planes of a,ba,b and a,ca,c: (a−b)⋅v=(a−b)⋅(a+b)/2(a−b)⋅v=(a−b)⋅(a+b)/2 and the common plane that contains a,b,ca,b,c. This gives you the center, and then distance to one of the points gives you a radius. The circle is then the intersection of the sphere and the common plane. – Dan Uznanski Apr 6 '17 at 21:37

You can also find first RR from the sin Law:

R=BC2sin(A)=BC⋅AB⋅AC2∥AB×AC∥(∗)(∗)R=BC2sin⁡(A)=BC⋅AB⋅AC2‖AB×AC‖

Next, write the equations of circles of radius RR with centre AA and BB and solve.

Note The formula (∗)(∗) is the well known geometric formula for the area of a triangle:

Area=abc4R.Area=abc4R.

Big hint:

Let A≡(1,1)A≡(1,1),B≡(2,4)B≡(2,4) and C≡(5,3)C≡(5,3).

We know that the perpendicular bisectors of the three sides of a triangle are concurrent.Join AA and BB and also BB and CC.

The perpendicular bisector of ABAB must pass through the point (1+22,1+42)(1+22,1+42)

Now find the equations of the straight lines AB and BC and after that the equation of the perpendicular bisectors of ABAB and BCBC.Solve for the equations of the perpendicular bisectors of ABAB and BCBC to get the centre of your circle.

Consider the general (implicit) equation that defines a circle, with parameters αα, ββ, γγ. Substitute the coordinate of the given points and get three linear equations in the three variables αα, ββ, γγ. Solve the system.

Given 3 points P1(x1,y1) ,P2(x2,y2), and P3(x3,y3), on circle circumference whose center is (h,k) .. circle equation for each pair of points can be expressed as:

(x1−h)2+(y1−k)2=(x2−h)2+(y2−k)2,(x1−h)2+(y1−k)2=(x2−h)2+(y2−k)2,
and
(x1−h)2+(y1−k)2=(x3−h)2+(y3−k)2,(x1−h)2+(y1−k)2=(x3−h)2+(y3−k)2,

By rearranging those equations, they can easily be put in the form of "difference of squares" in the form:

A2−B2=C2−D2A2−B2=C2−D2

we get :

(x1−h)2−(x2−h)2=(y2−k)2−(y1−k)2,(x1−h)2−(x2−h)2=(y2−k)2−(y1−k)2,
Where
A=(x1−h),B=(x2−h),C=(y2−k),D=(y1−k)A=(x1−h),B=(x2−h),C=(y2−k),D=(y1−k)
 Solving
A2−B2=(A−B)(A+B)A2−B2=(A−B)(A+B)
 we get:
[(x1−h)−(x2−h)][(x1−h)+(x2−h)]=[(y2−k)−(y1−k)]∗[(y2−k)+(y1−k)][(x1−h)−(x2−h)][(x1−h)+(x2−h)]=[(y2−k)−(y1−k)]∗[(y2−k)+(y1−k)]

simplifying:

(x1−x2)(x1+x2−2h)=(y2−y1)(y2+y1−2k)(x1−x2)(x1+x2−2h)=(y2−y1)(y2+y1−2k)

Introducing

a1=(x1−x2),a′1=(x1+x2),b1=(y2−y1),b′1=(y2+y1)a1=(x1−x2),a1′=(x1+x2),b1=(y2−y1),b1′=(y2+y1)
And
c1=(b1b′1−a1a′1)2a1c1=(b1b1′−a1a1′)2a1

we get for each pair of points :

h=b1a1k−c1h=b1a1k−c1
and another reduced equation for the other pair of points would give:
h=b2a2k−c2h=b2a2k−c2

Solving above equations , we get :

k=a1a2(c1−c2)(b1a2−b2a1)k=a1a2(c1−c2)(b1a2−b2a1)

and

r=(√E2+D2)r=(E2+D2)

Where

E=(x1−h)E=(x1−h)
and
D=(y1−k)D=(y1−k)

“Plücker’s mu” provides another way to do this. Choose two of the points, p1p1 and p2p2, and let the equations of two circles that pass through those points be f(x,y)=0f(x,y)=0 and g(x,y)=0g(x,y)=0. Every linear combination of these two equations is also that of a circle (perhaps degenerate) that passes through these points. Then, an equation of the circle that also passes through the point p0=(x0,y0)p0=(x0,y0) is f(x0,y0)g(x,y)−g(x0,y0)f(x,y)=0f(x0,y0)g(x,y)−g(x0,y0)f(x,y)=0. This method applies generally to point sets that are given as null sets of functions.

Sometimes the coordinates are such that one can build the two required functions by inspection, but one can always use the “degenerate circle”—the line between two of the points—in this construction. For example, taking p1=(1,1)p1=(1,1) and p2=(5,3)p2=(5,3), we can use the circle centered at their midpoint:

(x−3)2+(y−2)2=5(x−3)2+(y−2)2=5
and the double line through these points:
(x−2y+1)2=0.(x−2y+1)2=0.
The required equation is then
[(2−3)2+(4−2)2−5](x−2y+1)2−(3−2⋅4+1)2[(x−3)2+(y−2)2−5]=0,[(2−3)2+(4−2)2−5](x−2y+1)2−(3−2⋅4+1)2[(x−3)2+(y−2)2−5]=0,
which simplifies to (x−3)2+(y−2)2=5(x−3)2+(y−2)2=5. (This could also have been computed in matrix form, but that would’ve required expanding the equation of the line. In this case it was easier to work directly with the equations.)

I know this question is outdated, but I like to show this easy solution.

First subtract the coordinates of a point from the others'. Now we are looking for the equation of a circle through the origin and two other points, which is of the form

(x−xc)2+(y−yc)2−r2=x2−2xxc+y2−2yyc=0,(x−xc)2+(y−yc)2−r2=x2−2xxc+y2−2yyc=0,
as there is no independent term.

This results in the 2×22×2 linear system of equations

{2xcx1+2ycy1=x21+y22,2xcx2+2ycy2=x22+y22.{2xcx1+2ycy1=x12+y22,2xcx2+2ycy2=x22+y22.
giving the coordinates of the center and the radius x2c+y2c−−−−−−√xc2+yc2. Don't forget to translate back by adding the first point.

Coming back to this question because I was looking for ways to do this quickly on a computer. This problem becomes quite easy if we map each pair of (x,y)(x,y) points to three points in the complex plane of the form z=x+iyz=x+iy.

We now apply the linear transformation z→z−z1z2−z1z→z−z1z2−z1, which transforms the points [z1,z2,z3][z1,z2,z3] to the points [0,1,w=z3−z1z2−z1][0,1,w=z3−z1z2−z1].

We now square the relation |z−c|=r|z−c|=r for each point to find the following set of three equations:

|c|2=r2|c|2=r2
1−c−c¯+|c|2=r21−c−c¯+|c|2=r2
|w|2−w¯c−wc¯+|c|2=r2|w|2−w¯c−wc¯+|c|2=r2

Subtracting the first from the second and third equations gives us the series of equations:

[1w¯1w][cc¯]=[1|w|2][11w¯w][cc¯]=[1|w|2]
Invert the left hand side and multiply to get:
[cc¯]=1w−w¯[w−|w|2−w¯+|w|2][cc¯]=1w−w¯[w−|w|2−w¯+|w|2]

Note that this is singular if and only if w=w¯w=w¯, which is to say if ww is real, which means that the points [0,1,w][0,1,w] are collinear on the real axis. And since we applied a linear transformation, this only happens if the original points [z1,z2,z3][z1,z2,z3] were collinear in the complex plane to begin with!

The center of the circle can now be read off from the first row:

c′=w−|w|2w−w¯c′=w−|w|2w−w¯

But remember that we need to undo the linear transformation, so here is the answer in our original coordinates:

c=(z2−z1)w−|w|2w−w¯+z1c=(z2−z1)w−|w|2w−w¯+z1

The radius rr can be found from the equation before.

Or to make this nice and tidy, here is how you solve the problem in a few lines of MATLAB:

function circle_from_3_points(z1, z2, z3)
    w = (z3 - z1)/(z2 - z1);
    if isreal(w)
        disp('Points are collinear');
    else
        c = (z2 - z1)*(w - abs(w)^2)/(2i*imag(w)) + z1;
        r = abs(z1 - c);
        disp(c);
        disp(r);
    end
end

>> circle_from_3_points(1 + 1i, 2 + 4i, 5 + 3i);
      3.0000 + 2.0000i
      2.2361

>> circle_from_3_points(1 + 1i, 2 + 2i, 3 + 3i);
      Points are collinear

Thanks to David Wright of Oklahoma State University for this method.

As a programmer this was the best solution for me as there is no division by zero:

For given (x1,y1) , (x2,y2) and (x3,y3) first form A,B,C:

A=x1(y2−y3)−y1(x2−x3)+x2y3−x3y2A=x1(y2−y3)−y1(x2−x3)+x2y3−x3y2
B=(x21+y21)(y3−y2)+(x22+y22)(y1−y3)+(x23+y23)(y2−y1)B=(x12+y12)(y3−y2)+(x22+y22)(y1−y3)+(x32+y32)(y2−y1)
C=(x21+y21)(x2−x3)+(x22+y22)(x3−x1)+(x23+y23)(x1−x2)C=(x12+y12)(x2−x3)+(x22+y22)(x3−x1)+(x32+y32)(x1−x2)
D=(x21+y21)(x3y2−x2y3)+(x22+y22)(x1y3−x3y1)+(x23+y23)(x2y1−x1y2)D=(x12+y12)(x3y2−x2y3)+(x22+y22)(x1y3−x3y1)+(x32+y32)(x2y1−x1y2)

If A=0 then the points are colinear elasewhere using A,B,C you can find center and radius of circle:

xc=−B/2Axc=−B/2A
yc=−C/2Ayc=−C/2A

r=B2+C2−4AD4A2−−−−−−−−−−−−−√r=B2+C2−4AD4A2

Finally the formula of the circle is:

(x−xc)2+(y−yc)2=R2(x−xc)2+(y−yc)2=R2

Reference: http://www.ambrsoft.com/TrigoCalc/Circle3D.htm
